Advanced Joins
🧠 What are Advanced JOINs?
👉 When basic JOIN is not enough, we use:
SELF JOIN
FULL OUTER JOIN
CROSS JOIN
Multiple JOINs
Anti JOIN (very important 🔥)
---
1️⃣ SELF JOIN (Table joins with itself)
👉 Used when data is related within same table
🔹 Example: Employees & Managers
Table: employees
id	name	manager_id
1	Rahul 	   NULL
2	Amit	   1
3	Neha	   1
🔹 Query
SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m
ON e.manager_id = m.id;
🔹 Output
employee	manager
Rahul	NULL
Amit	Rahul
Neha	Rahul

🧠 Easy Meaning
👉 “Same table, different roles”
---
2️⃣ FULL OUTER JOIN
👉 Returns all data from both tables

🔹 Query
SELECT s.name, c.course
FROM students s
FULL OUTER JOIN courses c
ON s.id = c.student_id;

🔹 Output
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Amit	Linux
Neha	NULL
NULL	DevOps

⚠️ Note
👉 Not supported in some DBs like MySQL directly
(Use UNION workaround)
---
3️⃣ CROSS JOIN (Cartesian Product)
👉 Combines every row with every row

🔹 Query
SELECT s.name, c.course
FROM students s
CROSS JOIN courses c;

🔹 Output (3 × 3 = 9 rows)
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Rahul	Linux
Rahul	DevOps
Amit	AWS

🧠 Use Case
All combinations (product + size)
Testing data
---
4️⃣ Multiple JOINs (Real-world 🔥)
👉 Join more than 2 tables
🔹 Example
SELECT o.order_id, c.name, p.product_name
FROM orders o
JOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id
JOIN products p ON o.product_id = p.id;

🧠 Used in:
E-commerce systems
Banking
Analytics
---
5️⃣ ANTI JOIN (Very Important 🔥🔥)
👉 Find data NOT present in another table

🔹 Example: Students without courses
SELECT s.name
FROM students s
LEFT JOIN courses c
ON s.id = c.student_id
WHERE c.student_id IS NULL;

🔹 Output
name
Neha

🧠 Easy Meaning
👉 “Give me records with no match”
---
6️⃣ SELF JOIN vs NORMAL JOIN
Feature	SELF JOIN	NORMAL JOIN
Tables  	 Same	              Different
Use	             Hierarchy	  Relationships

